        | | A14 The Sunday Times Sunday, August 2, 2020 LEARNING LADDER M Gilbert Wong speaks to mid-level profession­als and educators on upskilling and staying relevant in a post-Covid-19 world r Nathan Khoo knew that a career in IT was something he wanted, but was unsure of what to specialise in.
Thankfully, he chanced upon the Graduate Diploma in Systems Analysis programme (GDipSA) offered by National University of Singapore’s Institute of Systems Science (NUS-ISS). The course provided him with the opportunit­y to explore a breadth of topics and fields, and paved his way to becoming a profession­al software engineer at Zühlke Engineerin­g. Formerly a newbie to the IT industry, he shares his thoughts on the course. Staying ahead of the curve The need to stay relevant by upskilling has become more crucial than ever, and the right educationa­l programme is key Getting a head start in tech Why do you think the GDipSA is relevant now? Before Covid-19 hit, companies have already been dealing with the pressure to digitalise and automate their operations. The pandemic has accelerate­d this trend by limiting physical interactio­n, requiring increased maintenanc­e of virtual operations.
Despite this challengin­g situation, the IT industry is thriving. For those looking to leverage such an opportunit­y, this programme represents an excellent starting point. M r David Han, manager (continuing education) at the Singapore campus o f James Cook U n i v e r s i t y ( JCUS) , s h a r e s why its Master of Business Administra­tion (MBA) programme offers flexibilit­y and various specialisa­tions to help working profession­als elevate their abilities. Entreprene­urship, Finance, Global Talent Management, and MICE, Tourism and Hospitalit­y — which enables them to learn essential analytical skills in business and apply them to their area of expertise. What is unique about this programme? With tech jobs currently in demand, it is becoming increasing­ly important to improve one’s informatio­n technology (IT) skills and knowledge to match the current job climate A variety of specialisa­tions is available, and prospectiv­e participan­ts can enrol in the programme through both academic and non-academic means.
Candidates may gain entry to the MBA with a relevant business-related Bachelor degree or higher, or a Bachelor degree or higher in other discipline­s with two years of business experience in a managerial role.
Candidates without these qualificat­ions may gain entry with a minimum of four years of business experience in a managerial role, and have demonstrat­ed effective management experience relating to organisati­onal behaviour, business, strategy, accounting, marketing, economics, communicat­ion and people.
Detailed entry requiremen­ts can be found on the JCUS website. Who is this course for? The MBA programme is ideal for those aspiring to take on managerial roles requiring a university degree, and business owners and senior management seeking to gain in-depth knowledge of various department­al functions.
The programme is also a potential pathway to a Doctor of Business Administra­tion (DBA), or PhD (Doctor of Philosophy). What did you enjoy about the course? The skills imparted by the course are incredibly useful both in and out of the workplace. Even if I find myself out of a job because of the economic downturn, I could leverage these skills for community or personal projects, which will also add value to my resume. for my personal projects. Even then, I found the GDipSA to be rigorous and challengin­g.
The course administer­s a group project to end off most modules. While some projects weren’t a particular­ly pleasing experience, I wouldn’t have as strong a foundation now had I not gone through them. This course was difficult for me, but the curriculum provided everything that I needed to succeed. IT industry. Experience­d profession­als in non-IT industries who recognise the need to equip themselves with the latest IT skills to advance their careers may apply as well. Singapore campus of James Cook University Master of Business Administra­tion Why is the MBA course relevant now? You have no formal IT background. How challengin­g did you find this course? National University of Singapore’s Institute of Systems Science Graduate Diploma in Systems Analysis As businesses evolve and industries change, it has become important to upgrade your skills and knowledge to excel in any organisati­on. With the MBA at JCUS, participan­ts can choose from a broad range of specialisa­tions within the course — Analytics and Business Solutions, Creative Marketing, How will the course be conducted? Who would benefit from this course? This course sets a high bar for the student in terms of its content. Before the course, I had already spent some time on beginner online programmin­g courses The course structure will consist of tutorials, lectures, research projects and presentati­ons conducted in-person and online. Full-time: 12 months The GDipSA is suitable for non-IT graduates intending to craft a new career path in the PRINTED AND DISTRIBUTE­D BY PRESSREADE­R PressReade­r.com +1 604 278 4604 ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY . ORIGINAL COPY COPYRIGHT AND PROTECTED BY APPLICABLE LAW
